issue_comment_body:
@ktbyers this should be good to go.

One thing maybe: it's writing bytes instead of strings. This isn't really a problem for my initial use case of writing to a file, but with the added functionality of writing to a buffer, user might expect that buffer to be string-based instead of bytes (like the return value of a `send_command()` call).

What do you think? Keep the bytes based approach? Or convert to strings? Usability-wise I think converting is better.

@stefbraun The pre-emphasis has been added. Please refer to [processing function](https://github.com/astorfi/speechpy/blob/master/speechpy/processing.py).

Thank you so much for your declared issue.
Bests

@davidhalter I agree with what you say. But still don't understand why we need object in this case.
We can define for example
```python
class FileState(object):

    def __init__(self, path, lines):
        self.path = path
        self.lines = lines


class FileChange(object):

    def __init__(self, initial_state, resulting_state):
        self.initial_state = initial_state
        self.resulting_state = resulting_state
```
and return list of FileChange objects

Corrected in the latest commit: 42ee99e62e52e47e0dcdcb5a842016a683b26bab
Will be available in Glances 3.0.

@towo Thanks for the issue report !

I have found out :

it should be like this :

- headers: {template: {"Authorization": $token_type $access_token,'Content-Type': 'application/hal+json;charset=UTF-8', 'Accept': 'application/json'}}

