However, there's **still** a problem with code in a _layer_ needing to run before any other code.  e.g. the situation where we want a package installed before code in a higher layer can run.

I wonder if some sort of specification for declaring the flags a layer is both dependent on _and_ provides for other layers to use. (So, this would make it explicit that the layer communicates some idea of 'state' to other layers).  Thus, the README for a layer would specifically indicate what preconditions _it_ expects with respect to other layers (i.e. all of it's handlers gate until a flag is true) and what postconditions it provides (e.g. a set of flags to indicate when it is ready).  Implementation detail might just be to gate internally.

This is already kind of implemented in interfaces which use '{relation-name}.connected' and '{relation-name'.available' as a (sort of) convention to indicate whether they can be consumed.

i.e. I'm advocating an explicit convention, and perhaps providing some framework support for detecting/supporting 'layer-level flags'.

TBD?

